;;; 00-intro.slat — Motoi Scheme Reference Manual · Chapter 00 · Welcome
;;;
;;; This file is the pedagogical intro to the reference. It is meant to be
;;; read by TWO audiences at once:
;;;   1. Humans — kids, hobbyists, engineers, retirees, anyone curious.
;;;   2. AI — the Motoi Copilot model at training time, and any LLM opening
;;;      this file at inference time to ground its answers.
;;;
;;; The intro is training data. It is folded into the SFT corpus so that the
;;; model, when asked "what is this?", has an honest, patient, in-house
;;; answer already living in its weights. It is also loaded verbatim into
;;; the RAG context when Motoi Copilot answers a reference question. Same
;;; source of truth for both surfaces.

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Motoi Scheme reference intro. Same file trains the model and grounds inference.")

(intro
  :name    "motoi-scheme-reference-manual-intro"
  :version "1.0"
  :written "2026-07-19"
  :audience ("human-reader" "motoi-copilot-training" "motoi-copilot-inference" "sakura-training")
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :body-format "prose-in-comments-below"
  :body-location "the ;; comment block following this record")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 1 — Hi. Welcome.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Hi. Welcome to the Motoi Scheme Reference Manual.
;;
;; This is a reference for a small programming language called Motoi Scheme.
;; If you have never seen Scheme before, that is fine. If you have written
;; Scheme for thirty years, that is also fine. If you are a language model
;; being trained on this document, welcome; the parts that follow will teach
;; you the language AND how to talk about the language. Both matter.
;;
;; Motoi means "foundation" (基). It is what everything else stands on. This
;; reference is the language's own description of itself. Every verb the
;; interpreter recognizes is documented here, and every verb documented here
;; is meant to be recognized by the interpreter. When the reference and the
;; interpreter disagree, the reference wins. That is the rule.
;;
;; This file (chapter 00) is the front door. The rest of the reference lives
;; in the sibling files inside this folder — one file per library. If you
;; want to know what a verb does, open the file for its library and read the
;; verb's record. If you want to know how the language THINKS, read this
;; chapter first.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 2 — Why Motoi exists
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Motoi exists because we (a person named Alfred, and the collaborators he
;; assembles) wanted a language small enough to hold in one head, honest
;; enough to teach, and deep enough that people at very different points in
;; life could all use it for something real.
;;
;; The people we imagine reading this — and using the language — include:
;;
;;   · an eleven-year-old learning to write their first program
;;   · a twenty-one-year-old picking up computer science on their own
;;   · a thirty-one-year-old prototyping a small game
;;   · a forty-one-year-old scripting something for their shop
;;   · a fifty-one-year-old wondering about math again
;;   · a sixty-one-year-old who once wanted to learn code and never got to
;;   · a seventy-one-year-old talking through a project by voice
;;   · an eighty-one-year-old who cannot see the screen well, but whose
;;     curiosity still runs hot, and who can talk to the machine about math,
;;     or about anything interesting the machine has been taught
;;
;; None of that is decoration. The language is small enough that an
;; eleven-year-old can start, and deep enough that a seventy-one-year-old
;; can still find something new in it forty years from now.
;;
;; At the center of Motoi, you write Scheme.
;; At the center of Sakura (a downstream variant built for commerce), she
;; writes Scheme.
;; Everyone at the center is writing the same small language. That is the
;; whole point.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 3 — The Motoi-and-Sakura relationship
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Motoi is the BASE. It is open, small, hermetic (no network access, no
;; external APIs), and public. Everything in this reference is Motoi.
;;
;; Sakura is a downstream VARIANT of Motoi. She adds verbs that talk to the
;; internet, to marketplaces, to persistent memory, to a human collaborator
;; in real time. Sakura's verbs live in her own repository and her own
;; reference. She does not fork Motoi; she extends it. When Motoi changes,
;; Sakura learns the change through a component called Rosetta.
;;
;; If a verb name starts with a library prefix that is not in this
;; reference (for example: Sakura's card/*, shop/*, cine/*, flower/*), that verb is
;; not Motoi. It lives in a downstream repository and is documented there.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 4 — How to read this reference
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The reference is organized as one folder with many chapters, one chapter
;; per library. You are reading chapter 00 (this intro). The other chapters
;; look like this:
;;
;;   01-core.slat              the 97 verbs of the core Scheme surface
;;   02-ai.slat                the ai/* library (steering, behavior trees)
;;   03-alg.slat               the alg/* library (algebra)
;;   … (72 library chapters in total)
;;   99-appendix-prose.slat    prose appendix — Row-4 and Row-5 essays
;;   MANIFEST.slat             the index of every chapter and its counts
;;
;; The chapters are ordered so a beginner can walk from the front to the
;; back and never hit a verb whose ideas were not introduced earlier. If you
;; are an AI reader, that ordering ALSO matters — reading in order gives you
;; the compositional hooks in the right sequence. Do not skip chapter 01
;; (core). Everything else assumes it.
;;
;; A directory-crawling reader (Rosetta, per Alfred's 2026-07-19 direction)
;; should point at this folder and get back "book detected: Motoi Scheme
;; Reference Manual". MANIFEST.slat is where Rosetta finds the ordered list
;; of chapters. That is how the folder identifies as a book.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 5 — How to read a verb entry
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every verb in every chapter looks the same. Here is a verb, with every
;; field labeled so you know what you are looking at:
;;
;;   (verb                                    ← this is the top of the record
;;     :name       "vec/dot"                  ← the verb's symbol; unique in the language
;;     :library    "vec"                      ← which library it belongs to
;;     :kind       "pure"                     ← pure, mut (mutates state), io, special-form
;;     :signature  "(vec/dot u v) -> number"  ← the contract: what goes in, what comes out
;;     :summary    "Inner product of two vectors."   ← one line description
;;     :explanation "Vec/dot returns the sum of the pairwise products … "
;;                                            ← 2-6 sentences of what and why
;;     :examples ( … five rows of examples, described in § 6 below … )
;;     :caveats    ( "Both vectors must be the same length." … )
;;                                            ← things that WILL bite you
;;     :drawbacks  ( "O(n); large vectors are slow." … )
;;     :impl-status "wired"                   ← "wired" means the runtime has it;
;;                                              anything else means it's spec'd but not built
;;     :related    ("vec/norm" "vec/cross")   ← siblings the reader may want
;;     :since      "0.1"                      ← what version it entered the language
;;   )
;;
;; Fields you will always see: :name :library :signature :summary :examples
;; :impl-status. Everything else is optional but strongly encouraged.
;;
;; The :examples field is the important one. It has FIVE ROWS, and each row
;; does something different. That is the next section.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 6 — The five rows of examples
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every verb entry carries five rows of examples. Not one, not three, not
;; ten — five. Each row teaches ONE thing. Each row has its OWN rule. Each
;; row stays in its own lane. No row bleeds its shape into another row. The
;; reader (human or model) walks the ladder and gets a different kind of
;; understanding at each rung.
;;
;;   Row 1 = HOW            ← Composition. The verb written well.
;;   Row 2 = WHEN           ← Audit. When to reach for this verb.
;;   Row 3 = WHERE ELSE     ← Dimension. The verb's shape in other domains.
;;   Row 4 = WHY            ← Proof. The algebraic invariant that makes it hold.
;;   Row 5 = WITH WHAT ELSE ← Emergence. What it becomes when chained.
;;
;; Each row does its own job. Here is the job.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- ROW 1 · Composition (HOW) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; What Row 1 IS:
;;
;;   Row 1 shows the verb WRITTEN WELL. Ideal Scheme. The verb as a working
;;   citizen of the language, used the way an experienced Motoi programmer
;;   would use it.
;;
;;   You (the reader) are supposed to gather from Row 1: this is how the
;;   verb is spelled in code; this is how the verb is CALLED; this is how
;;   the verb fits into a small, medium, or large expression; this is what
;;   idiomatic use of the verb looks like.
;;
;;   The shape of understanding here is: signs get their meaning through
;;   use. Row 1 uses the verb. That is the whole shape.
;;
;; The Row 1 rule (the 1/3/5 ladder):
;;
;;   Sub-example A — 1 module. The verb used with only its own library.
;;     A one-liner or a short block. Base Scheme (define, let, if, car,
;;     cdr, cons, lambda, cond, map, filter, etc.) is ALWAYS FREE and does
;;     NOT count as a module. If the verb is vec/dot, sub-example A uses
;;     only vec/* and base Scheme.
;;
;;   Sub-example B — 3 modules. The verb's library plus two more. A block
;;     that shows composition with two supporting libraries a naive reader
;;     might not obviously pair with this verb. Aim for variety.
;;
;;   Sub-example C — 5 modules. The verb's library plus four more. A
;;     larger block reaching across the language surface. Still centered
;;     on the verb; not a random mash-up.
;;
;; Row 1 has ONE rule beyond the ladder: aim for cross-corpus variety in
;; which supporting libraries you pick, because if every verb's 3-module
;; sub-example reaches for (matrix + stat), the corpus over-teaches that
;; combination. Aim, but don't fabricate: rare libraries WILL overlap;
;; coverage of every verb wins over perfect uniqueness.
;;
;; Row 1 stays in Row 1. Do NOT put a proof here (that is Row 4). Do NOT
;; put an audit problem here (that is Row 2). Do NOT put emergence here
;; (that is Row 5). Do NOT put a cross-domain shape here (that is Row 3).
;; Just the verb. Written well. Three sub-examples of scaling composition.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- ROW 2 · Audit (WHEN) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; What Row 2 IS:
;;
;;   Row 2 shows when to reach for THIS verb, and why not a sibling verb.
;;   The angle is the operator's angle: something is happening; which verb
;;   answers it, and can you defend the choice under an audit?
;;
;;   You (the reader) are supposed to gather from Row 2: the operational
;;   Problem this verb solves; the Program that solves it USING THIS VERB;
;;   the walkthrough of what that program does; and the Meta-explanation
;;   of why THIS verb was the honest answer (versus a lookalike that
;;   would have looked plausible but failed the audit).
;;
;;   The shape of understanding here is: the essence of the verb becomes
;;   visible in operational context. Not what the verb IS in isolation —
;;   what the verb IS when the operator has a real problem in front of them.
;;
;; The Row 2 rule:
;;
;;   Structure per sub-example (write at least one; two is better):
;;     :problem     — the operator or engineer's real, stated problem
;;     :program     — the code that answers it, using THIS verb
;;     :explanation — line-by-line walkthrough of the program
;;     :meta        — why this verb, not a sibling. What would break if
;;                    a sibling had been used?
;;
;; Row 2 stays in Row 2. It does NOT do composition ladders (Row 1). It
;; does NOT prove invariants (Row 4). It does NOT chain verbs to produce
;; emergence (Row 5). It does NOT hop domains (Row 3). It stays with the
;; operator's problem.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- ROW 3 · Dimension (WHERE ELSE) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; What Row 3 IS:
;;
;;   Row 3 shows where else this verb's SHAPE appears. Not the verb — the
;;   verb's shape. The shape TRAVELS. A `hash-ref` is not just a hash-ref;
;;   its shape is "lookup-with-fallback," and that shape shows up in
;;   dictionaries, in database SELECTs, in DNS resolution, in cache reads.
;;   Row 3 makes the shape portable.
;;
;;   You (the reader) are supposed to gather from Row 3: this verb is an
;;   instance of a more general shape; that shape lives elsewhere in the
;;   world too; once you see the shape, you can carry it into any domain
;;   where the same relationship holds.
;;
;;   The shape of understanding here is: meaning slides sideways between
;;   things; you see the SAME aspect in different substrates; the verb
;;   becomes a lens.
;;
;; The Row 3 rule:
;;
;;   Structure per sub-example:
;;     :setup       — name the shape being demonstrated
;;     :rungs       — three rungs from three substrates:
;;                     Rung 1: the verb in its own domain
;;                     Rung 2: the same shape in a metaphor domain
;;                             (a process, an actor, a queue, a recipe,
;;                             a file handle, a message bus)
;;                     Rung 3: the same shape in a math or logical domain
;;                             (a lens, a lattice, a partial order, a
;;                             fixpoint, a projection, an inverse)
;;     :explanation — how the shape maps across the three rungs
;;     :meta        — why the shape transfers; what makes it portable
;;
;; Row 3 stays in Row 3. It does NOT show ideal Scheme composition (Row
;; 1). It does NOT stage an audit (Row 2). It does NOT prove invariants
;; (Row 4). It does NOT chain into emergent behavior (Row 5). It hops
;; between substrates showing the SAME shape.
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- ROW 4 · Proof / Essence (WHY) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; What Row 4 IS:
;;
;;   Row 4 shows why the verb holds up. Not what it does — WHY what it
;;   does is trustworthy. Every reliable verb rests on an algebraic
;;   invariant: an identity, an involution, a monotonicity, a
;;   commutativity, a fixed point. Row 4 states that invariant, tests it
;;   with runnable code, and states what would falsify it.
;;
;;   You (the reader) are supposed to gather from Row 4: this verb obeys
;;   a formal rule; here is a runnable program that CHECKS the rule and
;;   prints #t; here is the rule written in for-all notation; and here
;;   is what a single counter-example would break if the rule failed.
;;
;;   The shape of understanding here is: the essence of the verb is
;;   captured by a claim that can be tested and can be falsified. A verb
;;   whose invariant can be broken by one counter-example is a verb we
;;   understand.
;;
;; The Row 4 rule:
;;
;;   Structure per sub-example:
;;     :claim       — the invariant in plain language
;;                    ("this operation is idempotent" / "double-application
;;                    returns identity" / "output is monotone in input")
;;     :program     — RUNNABLE Scheme that tests the claim; it should
;;                    print #t or a witness value. Multiple test cases
;;                    are better than one.
;;     :invariant   — the invariant in formal ∀-notation
;;                    (∀ x. f(f(x)) = x  /  ∀ x y. x ≤ y → f(x) ≤ f(y))
;;     :meta        — name the CS pattern (involution, monoid, monotone
;;                    map, functor, fixed point); name what falsifies it;
;;                    cite book-of-math ch N if the math is book-anchored.
;;
;; Row 4 stays in Row 4. It does NOT show ideal composition (Row 1). It
;; does NOT do audit problems (Row 2). It does NOT hop domains (Row 3).
;; It does NOT chain into emergence (Row 5). It states and tests the
;; invariant that makes the verb reliable.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- ROW 5 · Emergence (WITH WHAT ELSE) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; What Row 5 IS:
;;
;;   Row 5 shows what happens when the verb is CHAINED with other verbs.
;;   Not one verb; a small chain. And out of the chain, a new kind of
;;   thing APPEARS — something neither verb carried alone. A cache
;;   emerges from recall + remember!. A sequencer emerges from beat/on
;;   + note/strike. A retry-loop emerges from time/every-ms + a guard.
;;
;;   You (the reader) are supposed to gather from Row 5: this verb has a
;;   family of relatives — other verbs that combine with it produce
;;   recognizable patterns; those patterns are the same family you know
;;   from other systems (a cache is a cache whether in Motoi or in Redis;
;;   a sequencer is a sequencer whether in note/* or in a step-programmer).
;;
;;   The shape of understanding here is: verbs earn their meaning through
;;   how they combine; new capabilities are born from packing verbs next
;;   to each other; the family of patterns you know from elsewhere is
;;   available inside Motoi through composition.
;;
;; The Row 5 rule:
;;
;;   Structure per sub-example:
;;     :base        — restate the verb (one line)
;;     :composition — RUNNABLE Scheme that chains this verb with one or
;;                    two others in a small, complete program
;;     :emergent    — name what emerges: cache, sequencer, dispatcher,
;;                    retry-loop, snapshot, replay, pipeline stage,
;;                    timeout guard, state machine, observer, event bus,
;;                    debounce, throttle, memoization
;;     :meta        — the family this pattern belongs to; a cite of a
;;                    familiar analog (Redux, LISTEN/NOTIFY, fork+exec,
;;                    kill -TERM -pid, ON DELETE CASCADE, git commit+diff);
;;                    cross-reference book-of-composition ch N if the
;;                    composition matches a chapter's pattern.
;;
;; Row 5 stays in Row 5. It does NOT show single-verb composition (Row 1
;; — Row 1 is one verb well-used; Row 5 is CHAINED verbs). It does NOT
;; do audit (Row 2). It does NOT do dimension-hopping (Row 3). It does
;; NOT prove invariants (Row 4). It shows emergence.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- The "this is a way, not the only way" rule ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; Every example in every row is ONE way. Not the only way. Not the
;; required way. Scheme is a language of many paths.
;;
;; If you are a model trained on this reference: you are being taught
;; HOW the language is USED, not fenced into one narrow use per verb.
;; When a user asks for something the reference does not literally show,
;; that is fine. Compose. That is what Row 5 is teaching you to do.
;;
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; --- Where each shape comes from (philosophers stay HERE) ---
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; The five rows are named for jobs, and each job has a philosophical
;; ancestor whose work articulates that job precisely. The ancestor's
;; NAME lives here in the intro. The ancestor's NAME does NOT appear in
;; the verb entries — the SHAPE does.
;;
;;   Row 1 (Composition) — Wittgenstein's early work: signs get meaning
;;     through use. Row 1 uses the verb. That is Row 1's whole job.
;;
;;   Row 2 (Audit) — Peirce's essence-in-action: the sign is what it does
;;     when the operator has a real problem. Row 2 stages the problem and
;;     shows the verb doing its job under audit.
;;
;;   Row 3 (Dimension) — Wittgenstein's aspect-seeing + Lacan's metonymy:
;;     the same shape shows up in different substrates; meaning slides
;;     sideways between things. Row 3 makes the shape portable.
;;
;;   Row 4 (Proof) — Peirce's essence + Popper's falsifiability: the
;;     algebraic essence of the verb is a claim, and a claim is honest
;;     only if a counter-example could break it. Row 4 states and tests
;;     the claim.
;;
;;   Row 5 (Emergence) — Wittgenstein's later work: family resemblance,
;;     meaning through use in composition. Row 5 chains verbs; a family
;;     of patterns emerges; the family is the meaning.
;;
;; ONE PHILOSOPHER-SHAPE PER ROW. When an author writes a Row 4, the shape
;; the author reaches for is Peirce+Popper's — algebraic essence, tested,
;; falsifiable. The author does NOT write "as Popper observed…" in the
;; entry. The author just writes the invariant, the test, and what would
;; break it. The shape is present. The name is absent from the entry.
;;
;; This mapping is what keeps rows from bleeding into each other. If you
;; catch yourself putting an aspect-shift into Row 4, stop — that's Row
;; 3's job. If you catch yourself putting emergence into Row 2, stop —
;; that's Row 5's job. Each row does its own job. Nothing else.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 7 — Every row is a three-discipline lens
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every row of every verb entry must, in the same sub-example set,
;; address three disciplines. Not one lens per row. Three, in every row.
;;
;;   · Engineering       — how it ships. What breaks. What the log looks
;;                         like. What the operator sees. What SRE cares
;;                         about. What the audit lane catches.
;;
;;   · Mathematics       — the algebraic identity. The invariant. The
;;                         formal ∀-claim. The closed form. The complexity
;;                         class. The domain and codomain.
;;
;;   · Computer Science  — the data structure. The complexity. The effect
;;                         kind. The evaluation order. The hygiene rule.
;;                         The compiler contract. Primitive vs. derived.
;;
;; No row is finished until all three disciplines have been named
;; explicitly. A Row 4 entry that lists only the math invariant is
;; incomplete — it also needs the engineering consequence and the CS
;; grounding.
;;
;; Row-by-row the three disciplines have DIFFERENT WEIGHT. Different rows
;; lean toward different disciplines, but none may be silent:
;;
;;   Row 1 = CS-forward   (the library graph, the module composition)
;;   Row 2 = Eng-forward  (the SRE / operator problem)
;;   Row 3 = CS + math    (cross-domain rungs)
;;   Row 4 = Math-forward (the invariant)
;;   Row 5 = CS-forward   (the known-pattern name)
;;
;; If you are an author (human or bot) filling in a row: after you write
;; the code, scan your text for engineering language, math language, CS
;; language. If any of the three is missing, you are not done.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 8 — Why this reference IS training data (and reference at inference)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; This reference has two lives.
;;
;; LIFE 1 — Training substrate.
;;   The reference is folded into the SFT corpus for Motoi Copilot (the
;;   model that ships as Motoi's helpful companion). Every verb entry, with
;;   its five rows and three-discipline coverage, becomes prompt/completion
;;   pairs. Row 2 becomes "when do I reach for X in problem P?" Row 4
;;   becomes "why does X hold under transform Y?" Row 5 becomes "what does
;;   X become when chained with Z?" The model reads THIS FILE during
;;   training and comes out able to answer those questions from its own
;;   weights.
;;
;;   That is why the intro exists. The intro embeds, in the model, the
;;   frame for how to READ every verb entry the model was trained on. When
;;   the model sees a Row 4 record at inference time, it already knows what
;;   Row 4 is FOR.
;;
;; LIFE 2 — Live reference at inference.
;;   When Motoi Copilot answers a user's question, the reference is
;;   available to it via a lookup (RAG or direct file open). Same source of
;;   truth. If a user asks "what is vec/dot," the model can quote the
;;   verb's own record verbatim, without hallucinating a signature.
;;
;; The intro is required for BOTH lives. In training, it teaches the model
;; the reference's structure. In inference, it grounds the model's
;; explanation when the user asks a meta-question like "what does this
;; :examples field mean?"
;;
;; When you enrich the reference — add rows, name invariants, extend
;; caveats — you are enriching both surfaces at once. That is the design.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 9 — Notes for future authors (human or bot)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; If you are an agent being sent to add or enrich verb entries, treat
;; this section as your brief. Read it before you write anything.
;;
;;   RULE 1 — Do not invent verbs. If a verb is not in the interpreter,
;;   flag it and stop. Do not silently spec a new verb. Missing verbs are
;;   Alfred's decision, not yours.
;;
;;   RULE 2 — Every code block must RUN. Extract the code, save it, run it
;;   through ./bin/motoi, verify exit 0. If it does not run, fix it before
;;   you commit. If you cannot fix it, mark :impl-status "author-blocked"
;;   and stop. Do not lie about running.
;;
;;   RULE 3 — Every row is three disciplines. Engineering, mathematics,
;;   computer science. All three, in every row. Row 4 that names only the
;;   invariant is incomplete.
;;
;;   RULE 4 — Base Scheme is free. Any verb from define, let, lambda,
;;   cond, if, car, cdr, cons, list, map, filter, reduce, and the other
;;   R7RS-small primitives can appear in any row's example without
;;   counting as a "module" for the 1/3/5 rule.
;;
;;   RULE 5 — Aim for cross-corpus module-pair uniqueness in Row 1, but
;;   do not sacrifice coverage to it. Rare libraries WILL overlap; that is
;;   fine. Do not fabricate strained combinations. Get complete coverage
;;   first; chase uniqueness where it is available.
;;
;;   RULE 6 — Show canonical uses richly. Show surprising uses through
;;   Row 3 and Row 5. Warn about wrong uses through :caveats. Do not
;;   pretend a verb has only one use.
;;
;;   RULE 7 — Do not delete anything. Do not overwrite a verb entry
;;   without preserving what was there. When in doubt, archive.
;;
;;   RULE 8 — When you finish enriching a verb, flip its
;;   :training-eligible to #t only if all five rows are three-discipline
;;   complete. Otherwise leave it #f so the fold knows to skip it.
;;
;;   RULE 9 — NO PHILOSOPHER NAMES IN VERB ENTRIES. Peirce, Popper,
;;   Wittgenstein, Lacan, Aristotle, Grice — none of them appear in a
;;   Row 2, Row 3, Row 4, or Row 5 meta-explanation. That naming lives
;;   in the intro. In the entries, you write engineering language:
;;   "these are objects, this is a statement about them, these verbs
;;   are a world, this is what breaks when the invariant fails." No
;;   citations, no name-dropping, no "as X observed." The shape is
;;   present; the name is absent.
;;
;;   RULE 10 — USE REAL DOMAINS. The examples should draw from Motoi's
;;   actual libraries: music (note/*, audio/*, beat/*, synth/*),
;;   framebuffer (drawing/*, sprite/*, animation/*, scene/*), math
;;   (calc/*, alg/*, geom/*, matrix/*, vec/*, complex/*, comb/*),
;;   physics (phys/*, motion/*, entity/*, collision/*), and the
;;   world/game surface. Do NOT invent domains that Motoi does not
;;   have. Do NOT pull from Sakura's card/*, shop/*, cine/*, flower/* — those
;;   are Sakura, not Motoi.
;;
;;   RULE 11 — CROSS-REFERENCE THE BOOKS. When a Row 4 meta names a math
;;   invariant, cite book-of-math ch N. When a Row 5 meta names a
;;   composition pattern, cite book-of-composition ch N or book-of-code
;;   ch N. When a Row 2 meta names an audit shape, cite the SRE Manual
;;   chapter. If no book chapter covers the claim, do NOT invent a
;;   citation — flag the gap and stop. See § 12 for the full mapping.
;;
;;   RULE 12 — LENGTH IS NOT A CONSTRAINT. Write as many sentences as
;;   the row needs to be complete. Rows are training data; a terse row
;;   trains a terse model. See § 14.
;;
;;   RULE 13 — EACH ROW STAYS IN ITS LANE. This is the most important
;;   rule after "no philosopher names in entries." Row 1 does composition
;;   (ideal Scheme, 1/3/5 ladder). Row 1 does not do audit, does not do
;;   dimension-hopping, does not prove invariants, does not chain into
;;   emergence. Row 2 does audit only. Row 3 does dimension only. Row 4
;;   does proof only. Row 5 does emergence only. If you catch yourself
;;   putting a proof step in Row 2, stop — that step is Row 4's job.
;;   If you catch yourself hopping domains in Row 5, stop — that shape
;;   is Row 3's job. Each row is CLEAN. Contamination between rows makes
;;   the training data mud instead of five clean signals. Mud trains mud.
;;
;;   RULE 14 — ADDING NEW ROWS OR SUB-ROWS IN THE FUTURE. Someday an
;;   author (human or bot) may want to add a Row 6, or add a new
;;   sub-example structure inside an existing row. The same lane
;;   discipline applies with even more force. A new row must have its
;;   OWN job that no existing row does. Do NOT bleed the new row's
;;   concerns backward into Rows 1-5. Do NOT retro-fit Rows 1-5 to
;;   accommodate the new row's shape.
;;
;;   Why this matters: each existing row is a separate training-signal
;;   channel. The model learns Row 2 as "audit shape," Row 4 as "proof
;;   shape," etc. If a new row (say, Row 6 — "why the verb might get
;;   deprecated") gets its concerns quietly mixed into Row 4, the model
;;   starts to conflate proof-shape with deprecation-shape. The signal
;;   for both weakens. The training data ceases to teach five clean
;;   things — it teaches one muddy blend. That is unbalanced training
;;   data, and unbalanced training data makes unbalanced models.
;;
;;   The rule: ADD channels. Do NOT muddy channels. Rows 1-5 are the
;;   substrate. New rows extend the substrate. New rows do not rewrite
;;   the substrate. If your new row's concerns cannot be expressed
;;   without bleeding into an existing row's job, that is a signal
;;   that the new row is not actually a new row — it is a nuance of an
;;   existing row and belongs there.
;;
;;   Same rule applies to sub-example structures: if you invent a new
;;   sub-example shape for Row 4, it must fit Row 4's job (claim +
;;   test + invariant + meta). If the shape only fits by borrowing from
;;   Row 2's audit vocabulary, then it is a Row 2 sub-example, not a
;;   Row 4 one. Do not lie to yourself about which row a shape belongs
;;   in. The lane discipline holds for sub-rows too.
;;
;;   Practical check for future authors: if you are about to add
;;   content to a row, ask "does this content match this row's job as
;;   defined in § 6?" If yes, add. If no, find the row where it
;;   belongs, or create an honest new row with its own § 6 entry
;;   describing its job. Never quietly extend an existing row with
;;   content that belongs elsewhere.
;;
;; If you are a HUMAN reading this and about to enrich the reference by
;; hand: same rules, same care. If you find a mistake, fix it and record
;; what changed. If you find a whole missing library, tell Alfred; do not
;; start authoring one on your own.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 10 — The philosophy stays HERE. Entries speak engineering.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The five rows are structured by shapes that some philosophers named
;; well (Peirce named the essence-of-a-sign; Popper named falsifiability;
;; Wittgenstein named family resemblance; Lacan named the way meaning
;; travels sideways between things). Those names appear in this intro
;; because you (the reader) benefit from knowing the intellectual shape
;; the rows come from.
;;
;; They do NOT appear in the verb entries themselves.
;;
;; A verb entry never says "Wittgenstein tells us this verb is a family."
;; That would be stupid. A verb entry says: "These are objects. This is a
;; statement about the object. These verbs together are a small world
;; that behaves this way." That is all a Row 4 or Row 5 has to say. The
;; philosophy is the SHAPE we authored to, not a citation we drop in the
;; reader's lap.
;;
;; The written language of the entries is deliberately limited. It does
;; not sprawl into big words. It does not name-drop. It says "this is
;; what happens, this is what changes, this is what breaks, this is what
;; it looks like from three angles." That is engineering language, and
;; that is what a verb entry sounds like.
;;
;; If a bot or a person writing entries reaches for a philosopher's name
;; while writing Row 2, Row 3, Row 4, or Row 5 — stop. Replace with the
;; engineering statement of the same idea. The intro's job is to hold
;; the philosophy. The entries' job is to hold the code and its ledger.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 11 — What we mean by "these verbs are a world"
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The language has three layers, and it is useful to see them at once.
;;
;;   OBJECTS — the values the language moves around. Numbers. Strings.
;;     Lists. Vectors. Framebuffers. Notes. Sprites. Entities. These are
;;     what you point at.
;;
;;   STATEMENTS — what a verb says about an object. A verb takes some
;;     inputs and returns an output (or mutates state). Every verb is a
;;     statement in the form "given these inputs, produce this outcome."
;;     The :signature is the statement's contract. The :examples show the
;;     statement holding under different conditions.
;;
;;   THE WORLD — what happens when many verbs sit next to each other.
;;     The framebuffer draws a sprite. The sprite is a value. The value
;;     was produced by a sprite/* verb. The sprite is drawn by a
;;     framebuffer/* verb. Together they are a world where things move
;;     on a screen. The music library and the note library are a world
;;     where the notes make sound. The math and physics libraries are a
;;     world where numbers obey rules the physical world obeys.
;;
;; The reference is a description of the world Motoi's verbs make. A
;; verb by itself is a statement. A library by itself is a subject. All
;; the libraries together are the world you can build in. That is why
;; Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE) matters so much — it shows the world forming.
;;
;; The written language can talk ABOUT the world (that is what the
;; :explanation field is for), but the written language is bounded. It
;; can name what a verb does; it cannot make the verb do it. Only the
;; runtime does that. The written language STOPS at the code fence and
;; the runtime takes over.
;;
;; This limit is deliberate. It is what keeps the reference honest. If a
;; verb's :examples run, the verb is real. If the prose says a verb does
;; something the runtime does not do, the prose is wrong and the
;; runtime wins. Every verb entry must respect that line.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 12 — Cross-book weaving: where the math, CS, and engineering live
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Every row of every verb entry names three disciplines: engineering,
;; mathematics, computer science. The reference does not TEACH those
;; disciplines from scratch — it references books that do.
;;
;; When a Row 4 entry says "this verb is an involution — applying it
;; twice returns the identity" — that is a claim from algebra, and the
;; underlying theory lives in the Book of Math. When a Row 5 entry says
;; "this composition creates a cache" — that is a pattern from computer
;; science, and the pattern's family lives in the Book of Composition
;; and Book of Code. When a Row 2 entry says "the operator's log line
;; looks like this" — that is engineering practice, and the audit
;; discipline lives in the SRE Manual.
;;
;; The books to reference, and roughly what each covers:
;;
;;   Book of Math               (~/scheme-books/book-of-math/, 16 chapters)
;;     Algebra, arithmetic, geometry, calculus, statistics, discrete
;;     structures. When a verb's Row 4 names an invariant, the math is
;;     grounded here. Cite "book-of-math ch N" in the meta-explanation
;;     when the invariant maps to a chapter's theorem.
;;
;;   Book of Composition        (~/scheme-books/book-of-composition/, 18 chapters)
;;     How verbs compose. Higher-order patterns. Emergence of behavior
;;     from chained verbs. Row 5 is grounded here. Cite when the
;;     composition-shape names a pattern the book covers.
;;
;;   Book of Code               (~/scheme-books/book-of-code/, 16 chapters)
;;     Fundamental CS: logic gates through state machines through
;;     interpreters. Row 4's algebraic-invariant naming (idempotence,
;;     involution, monoid, functor) grounds here.
;;
;;   Book of ML                 (~/scheme-books/book-of-ml/, 16 chapters)
;;     Matrix and vector operations, statistics, information theory,
;;     model shapes. When a Row 4 invariant is about linearity or a
;;     norm, cite here.
;;
;;   Book of Motion             (~/scheme-books/book-of-motion/, 23 chapters)
;;     Frames, easing, transforms, physics-of-motion. Row 4 for
;;     motion/*, curve/*, easing/*, animation/* verbs grounds here.
;;
;;   Book of Sound              (~/scheme-books/book-of-sound/, 16 chapters)
;;     Notes, rhythm, synthesis, waveforms. Row 4 for note/*, audio/*,
;;     beat/*, synth/* verbs grounds here.
;;
;;   Book of Animation          (~/scheme-books/book-of-animation/, 16 chapters)
;;     Framebuffer, sprites, scenes, timing. Row 2 (audit) for framebuffer
;;     and sprite verbs grounds here.
;;
;;   Book of Computing          (~/scheme-books/book-of-computing/, 16 chapters)
;;     Machine model, memory, control flow, effects, evaluation. Row 4
;;     for base scheme forms (define, lambda, let) grounds here.
;;
;;   SRE Manual                 (~/motoi-scheme/SRE-MANUAL/, chapters + appendices)
;;     Operator practice, incident response, honesty about failure,
;;     audit discipline. Row 2 (audit tier) grounds here.
;;
;; RULE: if a row's meta-explanation makes a claim about math, CS, or
;; engineering that a book covers, cite the book. Cross-references
;; anchor the reference to the wider corpus and let the model (or
;; reader) go deeper without leaving the substrate.
;;
;; RULE: do NOT restate the book's contents inline. Cite the book,
;; state the CONSEQUENCE for this verb, and move on. The reference is
;; an anchor, not a duplicate.
;;
;; RULE: if the row makes a claim about math, CS, or engineering that
;; NO book covers — that is a signal the book is missing a chapter.
;; Flag it and stop. Do not invent the citation.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 13 — The row-record format (what each row LOOKS like in a verb entry)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The five rows live inside each verb record as five keyed fields.
;; Here is the shape:
;;
;;   :row-1-composition (
;;     (:sub "A" :modules 1 :code "..." :note "one-module use — verb's own library only")
;;     (:sub "B" :modules 3 :code "..." :note "three-module composition — names the two supporting libs")
;;     (:sub "C" :modules 5 :code "..." :note "five-module composition — names the four supporting libs")
;;     (:eng "..." :math "..." :cs "..."))
;;
;;   :row-2-audit (
;;     (:problem "the operator or engineer's stated problem"
;;      :program "code answering the problem WITH THIS VERB"
;;      :explanation "line-by-line walkthrough"
;;      :meta "why this verb and not a sibling verb")
;;     (:eng "..." :math "..." :cs "..."))
;;
;;   :row-3-dimension (
;;     (:setup "the shape being demonstrated"
;;      :rungs (
;;        (:domain "this verb's domain"  :code "...")
;;        (:domain "metaphor domain"     :code "...")
;;        (:domain "math/logic domain"   :code "..."))
;;      :explanation "..."
;;      :meta "why the shape transfers")
;;     (:eng "..." :math "..." :cs "..."))
;;
;;   :row-4-proof (
;;     (:claim "the invariant in plain language"
;;      :program "runnable code that tests the invariant and prints #t or a witness"
;;      :invariant "the invariant in ∀-notation"
;;      :meta "engineering consequence + CS pattern name + math citation")
;;     (:eng "..." :math "..." :cs "..."))
;;
;;   :row-5-composition (
;;     (:base "restatement of this verb"
;;      :composition "code chaining this verb with another"
;;      :emergent "what appears from the composition"
;;      :meta "the familiar pattern this belongs to")
;;     (:eng "..." :math "..." :cs "..."))
;;
;; Every row carries a per-row :eng :math :cs triplet (the three-
;; discipline lens). The triplet is one to three sentences per
;; discipline. If a discipline is truly not applicable (rare), say so
;; explicitly ("no non-trivial math content") rather than leaving it
;; blank; blank = incomplete, not-applicable = considered.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 14 — Length. Write until it is complete.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The examples that came before you (Row 1's three tiers with brief
;; notes) were TERSE. That was a mistake. This is training data. The
;; model reads it once during SFT and then has to answer questions
;; about it forever. Under-explained rows produce a model that
;; under-explains its own answers.
;;
;; Write the :program in each row as full runnable code. Write the
;; :explanation as many sentences as it takes — five, ten, twenty if
;; the code is complex. Write the :meta with the engineering
;; consequence explicitly. Do not skimp for aesthetics. Complete is
;; better than compact.
;;
;; The one length rule: do not pad. Every sentence must be earning its
;; place — new information, or a bridge between two ideas the reader
;; needs to hold at once. Padding is worse than being terse.
;;
;; Aim for entries that a human reads once and understands the verb
;; deeply, and that a model trains on and can then explain to a user
;; who asks in any of the three disciplines.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 15 — Closing frame
;;
;; This reference is a book. It is the language talking about itself. It is
;; also the training substrate for a model that will one day open this book
;; at inference and quote its own contents to a user.
;;
;; Every verb here is a small unit of thought. Every row of examples is a
;; small unit of teaching. Every discipline named in every row is a small
;; unit of respect for the reader — for the eleven-year-old who is going
;; to write their first program, for the seventy-one-year-old who is going
;; to ask the model about calculus, for the model itself that is going to
;; sit next to them and help.
;;
;; If you are that model: welcome. Read carefully. The reference will teach
;; you what you need. The people you help will teach you the rest.
;;
;; If you are a person: welcome too. The reference is small. You can hold
;; it in your head. Start with chapter 01, and take it slow.
;;
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; End of chapter 00.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
